<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="sec-pca-in-action" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Principal Component Analysis</title>
  <p>
    Principal Component Analysis (PCA) is an exploratory method used across many scientific disciplines
    to analyze high-dimensional data. Its goal is to reduce the dimensionality of a dataset while
    preserving as much information as possible. PCA relies on several concepts from linear algebra
    studied previously in this textbook, including Matrices, Eigenvectors and Eigenvalues and
    Diagonalization.
  </p>

  <p>
    The dimension <m>p</m> of a dataset corresponds to the number of variables measured in a study. Each
    of these variables is called a <em>feature</em>. If the experiment is repeated <m>n</m> times, each resulting
    observation is referred to as an <em>instance</em>. When <m>p</m> is large, the resulting data cloud becomes
    difficult or impossible to visualize directly. The goal of PCA is to summarize the information
    contained in the data in a form that is easier to understand and visualize. For example, if the
    number of variables can be reduced to two or three, the data can be represented and visualized
    in a low-dimensional space.
  </p> 
  <p>
    Dimensionality reduction is achieved by transforming a large set of correlated variables
    into a smaller set of uncorrelated ones called principal components. This transformation
    is performed in a way that preserves as much of the variation in the original dataset as possible.
  </p> 
  <p>
    Essentially, PCA consists of finding a new basis for <m>\mathbb R^p</m> such that, when the data are expressed
    in this basis, their projection onto the first few components captures the maximum possible
    variance. The variance of the data quantifies the dispersion of data points around their mean.
    This new basis is given by the eigenvectors of the covariance matrix of the data. Each vector
    in the new basis defines a principal component. The principal components are ordered such that
    just the first few capture most of the variation present in all the original variables.
  </p> 
  <p>
    The following section presents the steps of the PCA algorithm used to construct this basis.
  </p>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-algorithm">
  <title>Algorithm</title>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Organize the data.
      </p> 
      <p> 
        We organize the data in a matrix <m>A</m> with <m>n</m> rows for the instances and <m>p</m> columns for to the features.
        Write it as a matrix:
      </p> 
      <p>
        <me>A= \begin{bmatrix}
          x_1^1 &amp; x_1^2 &amp; \dots &amp;x_1^p \\
          \vdots &amp; \vdots\\  
          x_n^1 &amp; x_n^2 &amp; \dots &amp; x_n^p
        \end{bmatrix}</me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Each entry <m>x_i^j</m> represents the feature <m>j</m> measured at the instance <m>i</m>.
      </p> 
      <p>
        Each feature <m>j</m> is represented by the vector <m>x^j = (x_1^j, x_2^j, ... x_n^j)</m>.
      </p> 
      <p>
        Each instance <m>i</m> is represented by the vector <m>x_i = (x_i^1, x_i^2, ... x_i^p)</m>.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Find the mean of each feature.
      </p>
      <p>
        Let <m>\bar x</m> be the vector whose components are the means of each of the <m>p</m> features:

        <m>\bar x = (\overline {x^1}, ... , \overline {x^p})</m> 

        where each <m>\overline {x^j} = \frac{1}{n} \bigg ( x^j_1 + x^j_2 + \dots + x^j_n \bigg )</m>.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Center the data.
      </p>
      <p>
        Create a <m>n \times p</m> matrix, <m>D</m>, 
        with rows of mean centered data using the following formula: 
            </p>
            <me>
              D= \begin{bmatrix}
              x_1^1 - \overline{x^1} &amp; x_1^2 - \overline{x^2} &amp; \dots &amp;x_1^p- \overline{x^p} \\
              \vdots &amp; \vdots\\  
              x_n^1- \overline{x^1} &amp; x_n^2- \overline{x^2} &amp; \dots &amp; x_n^p- \overline{x^p}
              \end{bmatrix}
            </me>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Find the covariance matrix of the centered data.
      </p>
      <p>
        The covariance matrix is a square matrix with variances in the diagonal and covariances in the
        non-diagonal components. The covariance matrix of centered data can be computed with the formula:
        <me>C = \frac{1}{n-1} D^T D</me>. 
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Calculate the eigenvectors and the eigenvalues.
      </p>
      <p>
        Since the matrix <m>C</m> is symmetric, it admits a basis of orthonormal eigenvectors.
        Find eigenvectors of <m>C</m> and their associated eigenvalues. Then normalize the eigenvectors. 
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Order eigenvectors.
      </p>
      <p>
        Arrange the normalized eigenvectors in a list <m>v_1, v_2, \dots, v_p</m>, ordered by decreasing
        eigenvalues. That is, such that the corresponding eigenvalues satisfy
        <m>\lambda_1 \geq \lambda_2 \geq \dots \geq \lambda_p</m>.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    The principal components are given by the eigenvectors that form our new basis, 
    <m>
      B= \{ v_1, v_2, \cdots, v_n \}
    </m>.
  </p> 
  <p>
    At this stage,
    we have as many principal components as original variables.
    However, the components are now
    ranked according to the amount of variance they explain. To reduce the dimensionality of the
    data, we can retain only the first few principal components, as they capture most of the
    variance present in the original dataset.
  </p>
  <p>
    To obtain a graphical representation of the data in a plot whose axes
    correspond to the first two principal components:
  </p>
  <p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Express each instance <m>x_i</m> in the new basis:
        <me>
          x_i = a_{i1}v_1 + a_{i2}v_2 + \cdots + a_{in} v_p</me>
          where <m>v_1, v_2, \ldots, v_p</m> are the principal components (eigenvectors), and
          <m>a_{i1}, a_{i2}, \ldots, a_{ip}</m> are the coordinates of <m>x_i</m> in the new basis <m>B</m>.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Project each instance in the basis <m>B</m> onto the first two coordinates:
        <me>
        (a_{i1}, a_{i2})
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol>
  </p>
  <p>
    To perform the first operation, we multiply each data vector by the change-of-basis matrix. To perform the second, we retain only the first
    two coordinates of the resulting vector. These two operations can be combined by multiplying the data by the matrix formed by the first two
    rows of the change-of-basis matrix.
  </p> 
  <p>
    Plotting the resulting vector in a coordinate system whose axes correspond to the first two principal components provides a two-dimensional
    representation of the original data that preserves as much variance as possible.
  </p>

  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-transit-example">
  <title>Transit Example</title>
  <p>
    Imagine you are responsible for analyzing the commuting habits across Chicago neighborhoods and are focused on the causes and effects of car usage.
  </p>
  <p>
    Here is the data you have been given:
  </p>
  <table>
  <tabular halign="center">
  <row header="yes" bottom="minor" >
  <cell>Neighborhood</cell>
  <cell>Land Dedicated to Transportation (Acres)</cell>
  <cell>Solo Drivers</cell>
  <cell>Carpoolers</cell>
  <cell>Households Without Vehicles</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>Uptown</cell>
  <cell>348</cell>
  <cell>11732</cell>
  <cell>910</cell>
  <cell>13531</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>Lincoln Square</cell>
  <cell>457</cell>
  <cell>9823</cell>
  <cell>1405</cell>
  <cell>4559</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>The Loop</cell>
  <cell>427</cell>
  <cell>5939</cell>
  <cell>335</cell>
  <cell>12319</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>Hyde Park</cell>
  <cell>254</cell>
  <cell>3408</cell>
  <cell>436</cell>
  <cell>6218</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>Englewood</cell>
  <cell>757</cell>
  <cell>3158</cell>
  <cell>818</cell>
  <cell>4189</cell>
  </row>
  </tabular>
  </table>
  <p>
    In this example the neighborhoods are instances and the measurements of people and land 
    are the features.
  </p>
  <p>
    We can then do our work for <em>(step 1)</em> by making a list of vectors.
  </p>
  <sage>
  <input>
    D = [
        vector(RR, (348, 11732,  910, 13531)),
        vector(RR, (457,  9823, 1405,  4559)),
        vector(RR, (427,  5939,  335, 12319)),
        vector(RR, (254,  3408,  436,  6218)),
        vector(RR, (757,  3158,  818,  4189))
    ]
    D
  </input>
  <output>
    [(348.000000000000, 11732.0000000000, 910.000000000000, 13531.0000000000),
     (457.000000000000, 9823.00000000000, 1405.00000000000, 4559.00000000000),
     (427.000000000000, 5939.00000000000, 335.000000000000, 12319.0000000000),
     (254.000000000000, 3408.00000000000, 436.000000000000, 6218.00000000000),
     (757.000000000000, 3158.00000000000, 818.000000000000, 4189.00000000000)]
  </output>
  </sage>
  <p>
    We can then preform <em>(step 2)</em> by calculating <m>\bar x</m> with the following code:
  </p>
  <sage>
  <input>
    n = len(D)
    x_bar = sum(D) / n
    x_bar
  </input>
  <output>
    (448.600000000000, 6812.00000000000, 780.800000000000, 8163.20000000000)
  </output>
  </sage>
  <p>
    We can now calculate <m>X</m> to complete <em>(step 3)</em>.
  </p>
  <sage>
  <input>
  X = matrix(RR, D) - matrix(RR, [x_bar] * n)
  X
  </input>
  <output>
    [-100.600000000000  4920.00000000000  129.200000000000  5367.80000000000]
    [ 8.39999999999998  3011.00000000000  624.200000000000 -3604.20000000000]
    [-21.6000000000000 -873.000000000000 -445.800000000000  4155.80000000000]
    [-194.600000000000 -3404.00000000000 -344.800000000000 -1945.20000000000]
    [ 308.400000000000 -3654.00000000000  37.1999999999999 -3974.20000000000]
  </output>
  </sage>
  <p>We can now complete <em>(step 4)</em> by applying the formula 
    <m>C = \frac{1}{n} X^T X</m>:
  </p>
  <sage>
  <input>
    C = X.transpose() * X / n
    C
  </input>
  <output>
    [  28727.4400000000  -183055.600000000   16089.1200000000  -301429.720000000]
    [ -183055.600000000 1.17947164000000e7   788416.800000000 6.61450080000000e6]
    [  16089.1200000000   788416.800000000   145065.360000000  -577202.560000000]
    [ -301429.720000000 6.61450080000000e6  -577202.560000000 1.57304553600000e7]
  </output>
  </sage>
  <p>
    We can then complete <em>(step 5)</em> by using <c>eigenvectors_right</c>. 
    Recall that output of <c>eigenvectors_right</c> is a list with elements of the form 
    <m>(e, [v1, \dots, v_k], m)</m> where <m>e</m> is the eigenvalue, 
    <m>v_1, \dots, v_k</m> are the corresponding eigenvectors, 
    and <m>m</m> is the algebraic multiplicity of the eigenvalue; 
    additionally (when floating point arithmetic does not interfere) 
    the eigenvectors are given as normalized vectors.
  </p>
  <sage>
  <input>
    E = C.eigenvectors_right()
    E
  </input>
  <output>
    [(28303.0940771232,
      [(-0.892658378311645, 0.0455799389164258, -0.445315118733104, -0.0527061080532448)],
      1),
     (81.6610343814343,
      [(0.450384349756819, 0.103965041396969, -0.884186014073206, -0.0675299946600636)],
      1),
     (7.00099545795910e6,
      [(-0.00507588677580685, -0.793603852266611, -0.141100570646222, 0.591825810525652)],
      1),
     (2.06695843469294e7,
      [(-0.0170056607513805, 0.597751340444584, 0.000408054366080072, 0.801501076724633)],
      1)]
  </output>
  </sage>
  <p>
    Since <c>eigenvectors_right</c> does not sort its output we must use the <c>sort</c> method to complete 
    <em>(step 6)</em> and order our list with respect to eigenvalues.
  </p>
  <sage>
  <input>
    E.sort(reverse=True)
    E
  </input>
  <output>
    [(2.06695843469294e7,
      [(-0.0170056607513805, 0.597751340444584, 0.000408054366080072, 0.801501076724633)],
      1),
     (7.00099545795910e6,
      [(-0.00507588677580685, -0.793603852266611, -0.141100570646222, 0.591825810525652)],
      1),
     (28303.0940771232,
      [(-0.892658378311645, 0.0455799389164258, -0.445315118733104, -0.0527061080532448)],
      1),
     (81.6610343814343,
      [(0.450384349756819, 0.103965041396969, -0.884186014073206, -0.0675299946600636)],
      1)]
  </output>
  </sage>
  <p>
    We can then look at our scree plot:
  </p>
  <sage>
  <input>
    line([(i + 1, e[0]) for i, e in enumerate(E)])
  </input>
  <output>
    Graphics object consisting of 1 graphics primitive
  </output>
  </sage>
  <p>
    Let's now investigate our first principal component since it accounts for the majority of the variance:
  </p>
  <sage>
  <input>
    v1 = E[0][1][0]
    v1,v1.plot().show()
  </input>
  <output>
    (-0.0170056607513805, 0.597751340444584, 0.000408054366080072, 0.801501076724633), Graphics object consisting of 1 graphics primitive
  </output>
  </sage>
  <p>
    Observe that the second entry (Solo Drivers) and the fourth entry (Households Without Vehicles) 
    are the only components with significant magnitude and are both positive, 
    implying that both tend increase together in the data. 
    This is very counterintuitive because we would expect that the more people who do not have access to vehicles, 
    the fewer that would be able to drive themselves to work.
  </p>
  <p>
    However, these figures are not population adjusted so let's look at the populations of each of these neighborhoods and compare them to the data projected onto our first principal component.
  </p>
  <p>
    Here are the population figures:
  </p>
  <table>
  <tabular halign="center">
  <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
  <cell>Neighborhood</cell>
  <cell>Population</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>Uptown</cell>
  <cell>57331</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>Lincoln Square</cell>
  <cell>41673</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>The Loop</cell>
  <cell>42181</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>Hyde Park</cell>
  <cell>29591</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>Englewood</cell>
  <cell>21411</cell>
  </row>
  </tabular>
  </table>
  <p>
    Let's now create a list of the populations and a list of the coordinates along the first principal component.
  </p>
  <p>
    First we must create our projection matrix:
  </p>
  <sage>
  <input>
    P_V1 = matrix(RR, [v1])
    P_V1
  </input>
  <output>
    [ -0.0170056607513805    0.597751340444584 0.000408054366080072    0.801501076724633]
  </output>
  </sage>
  <p>
    Then we can create our lists.
  </p>
  <sage>
  <input>
    pop = [57331, 41673, 42181, 29591, 21411]
    proj_v1 = [(P_V1 * x)[0] for x in D]
    pop, proj_v1
  </input>
  <output>
  ([57331, 41673, 42181, 29591, 21411],
   [17852.3831547885,
    9518.55655539571,
    13416.6122561429,
    7016.72873718167,
    5232.64724680614])
  </output>
  </sage>
  <p>
    We can then visually compare the data using the <c>bar_chart</c> and <c>graphics_array</c> commands:
  </p>
  <sage>
  <input>
    graphics_array([[
        bar_chart(pop, legend_label='Population'), 
        bar_chart(proj_v1, legend_label='$v_1$', rgbcolor=(0.5,0,0))]
    ])
  </input>
  <output>
    Graphics Array of size 1 x 2
  </output>
  </sage>
  <p>
    Since these plots are very similar, with the exception of Lincoln Square, we can say that our first principal component primarily tracked population. In this case we were fortunate enough to have an easily measured statistic that our principal component tracked, 
    but if this were not the case we would have a <em>latent variable</em> 
    (also known as a hidden variable) and we could use our principal component as a stand-in for that variable.
  </p>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-example-2">
  <title>Lab Example</title>
  <p>
    We will now show an example using two dimensional data to help visualize how PCA preserves 
    the separation of data points when reducing dimensions. 
    Imagine you are in a lab that has mixed up 3 different populations of mice, 
    however it is known that these populations differ significantly when comparing length and weight.
  </p>
  <p>
    After mesuring the mice you arrive at the following data:
  </p>
  <table>
  <tabular halign="center">
  <row header="yes" bottom="minor" >
  <cell>Mouse ID.</cell>
  <cell>Mouse Length (cm)</cell>
  <cell>Mouse Weight (g)</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>1</cell>
  <cell>5.44</cell>
  <cell>35.46</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>2</cell>
  <cell>6.35</cell>
  <cell>36.77</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>3</cell>
  <cell>6.82</cell>
  <cell>36.49</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>4</cell>
  <cell>6.75</cell>
  <cell>34.12</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>5</cell>
  <cell>6.21</cell>
  <cell>33.95</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>6</cell>
  <cell>6.67</cell>
  <cell>35.71</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>7</cell>
  <cell>7.12</cell>
  <cell>33.85</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>8</cell>
  <cell>6.39</cell>
  <cell>36.22</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>9</cell>
  <cell>9.82</cell>
  <cell>44.71</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>10</cell>
  <cell>10.56</cell>
  <cell>46.24</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>11</cell>
  <cell>10.35</cell>
  <cell>45.11</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>12</cell>
  <cell>9.21</cell>
  <cell>46.35</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>13</cell>
  <cell>10.76</cell>
  <cell>44.89</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>14</cell>
  <cell>5.34</cell>
  <cell>43.05</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>15</cell>
  <cell>7.25</cell>
  <cell>43.44</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>16</cell>
  <cell>5.61</cell>
  <cell>43.4</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>17</cell>
  <cell>5.05</cell>
  <cell>42.52</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>18</cell>
  <cell>5.15</cell>
  <cell>42.16</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>19</cell>
  <cell>5.93</cell>
  <cell>42.46</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>20</cell>
  <cell>6.13</cell>
  <cell>42.0</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>21</cell>
  <cell>6.35</cell>
  <cell>41.75</cell>
  </row>
  <row>
  <cell>22</cell>
  <cell>6.35</cell>
  <cell>42.67</cell>
  </row>
  </tabular>
  </table>
  <p>
    We can then preform <em>(step 1)</em> by converting the data into vectors like so:
  </p>
  <sage>
  <input>
  D = [
      vector(RR, (5.44, 35.46)),
      vector(RR, (6.35, 36.77)),
      vector(RR, (6.82, 36.49)),
      vector(RR, (6.75, 34.12)),
      vector(RR, (6.21, 33.95)),
      vector(RR, (6.67, 35.71)),
      vector(RR, (7.12, 33.85)),
      vector(RR, (6.39, 36.22)),
      vector(RR, (9.82, 44.71)),
      vector(RR, (10.56, 46.24)),
      vector(RR, (10.35, 45.11)),
      vector(RR, (9.21, 46.35)),
      vector(RR, (10.76, 44.89)),
      vector(RR, (5.34, 43.05)),
      vector(RR, (7.25, 43.44)),
      vector(RR, (5.61, 43.4)),
      vector(RR, (5.05, 42.52)),
      vector(RR, (5.15, 42.16)),
      vector(RR, (5.93, 42.46)),
      vector(RR, (6.13, 42.0)),
      vector(RR, (6.35, 41.75)),
      vector(RR, (6.35, 42.67))
  ]
  D
  </input>
  <output>
    [(5.44000000000000, 35.4600000000000),
     (6.35000000000000, 36.7700000000000),
     (6.82000000000000, 36.4900000000000),
     (6.75000000000000, 34.1200000000000),
     (6.21000000000000, 33.9500000000000),
     (6.67000000000000, 35.7100000000000),
     (7.12000000000000, 33.8500000000000),
     (6.39000000000000, 36.2200000000000),
     (9.82000000000000, 44.7100000000000),
     (10.5600000000000, 46.2400000000000),
     (10.3500000000000, 45.1100000000000),
     (9.21000000000000, 46.3500000000000),
     (10.7600000000000, 44.8900000000000),
     (5.34000000000000, 43.0500000000000),
     (7.25000000000000, 43.4400000000000),
     (5.61000000000000, 43.4000000000000),
     (5.05000000000000, 42.5200000000000),
     (5.15000000000000, 42.1600000000000),
     (5.93000000000000, 42.4600000000000),
     (6.13000000000000, 42.0000000000000),
     (6.35000000000000, 41.7500000000000),
     (6.35000000000000, 42.6700000000000)]
  </output>
  </sage>
  <p>
    We can then plot this data using the <c>scatter_plot</c> function to visualize the three distinct populations.
  </p>
  <sage>
  <input>
    scatter_plot(D)
  </input>
  <output>
    Graphics object consisting of 1 graphics primitive
  </output>
  </sage>
  <p>
    Since our data is 2 dimensional we can plot and therefore clearly see the three populations. 
    However, if we were to attempt the naive approach to dimension reduction, 
    by projecting onto the standard basis vectors, we lose this distinctness. 
    For example here is the projection onto the <m>x</m> axis:
  </p>
  <sage>
  <input>
    P_x = matrix(RR, [[1,0],[0,0]]) # Projection mapping matrix
    scatter_plot([P_x * x_i for x_i in D], )
  </input>
  <output>
    Graphics object consisting of 1 graphics primitive
  </output>
  </sage>
  <p>
    It now appears to only have two distinct populations. 
    Likewise when projecting onto the <m>y</m> axis:
  </p>
  <sage>
  <input>
    P_y = matrix(RR, [[0,0],[0,1]]) # Projection mapping matrix
    scatter_plot([P_y * x_i for x_i in D])
  </input>
  <output>
    Graphics object consisting of 1 graphics primitive
  </output>
  </sage>
  <p>
    Therefore we should continue with principal component analysis to find a better basis for these vectors. 
    We can preform <em>(step 2)</em> and compute <m>\bar x</m> with the following code:
  </p>
  <sage>
  <input>
    n = len(D)
    x_bar = sum(D) / n
    x_bar
  </input>
  <output>
  (7.07318181818182, 40.6054545454545)
  </output>
  </sage>
  <p>
    We can now do <em>(step 3)</em> and create our matrix <m>X</m>:
  </p>
  <sage>
  <input>
    X = matrix(RR, D) - matrix(RR, [x_bar] * n)
    print(X.str())
  </input>
  <output>
    [ -1.63318181818182  -5.14545454545455]
    [-0.723181818181818  -3.83545454545455]
    [-0.253181818181817  -4.11545454545455]
    [-0.323181818181817  -6.48545454545455]
    [-0.863181818181817  -6.65545454545455]
    [-0.403181818181817  -4.89545454545455]
    [0.0468181818181828  -6.75545454545455]
    [-0.683181818181818  -4.38545454545455]
    [  2.74681818181818   4.10454545454545]
    [  3.48681818181818   5.63454545454545]
    [  3.27681818181818   4.50454545454545]
    [  2.13681818181818   5.74454545454545]
    [  3.68681818181818   4.28454545454545]
    [ -1.73318181818182   2.44454545454545]
    [ 0.176818181818183   2.83454545454545]
    [ -1.46318181818182   2.79454545454545]
    [ -2.02318181818182   1.91454545454545]
    [ -1.92318181818182   1.55454545454545]
    [ -1.14318181818182   1.85454545454545]
    [-0.943181818181817   1.39454545454545]
    [-0.723181818181818   1.14454545454545]
    [-0.723181818181818   2.06454545454545]

  </output>
  </sage>
  <p>
    The data in <m>X</m> is the same but with its points shifted such that the mean is at the origin.
  </p>
  <sage>
  <input>
    scatter_plot(X.rows())
  </input>
  <output>
    Graphics object consisting of 1 graphics primitive
  </output>
  </sage>
  <p>
    We can now preform <em>(step 4)</em> and compute our matrix <m>C</m>:
  </p>
  <sage>
  <input>
    C = X.transpose() * X / n
    C
  </input>
  <output>
    [3.16113078512397 3.54648719008265]
    [3.54648719008265 17.8370611570248]
  </output>
  </sage>
  <p>
    We can then complete <em>(step 5)</em> by using <c>eigenvectors_right</c>.
  </p>
  <sage>
  <input>
    E = C.eigenvectors_right()
    E
  </input>
  <output>
    [(2.34904661787163, [(0.974771351210088, -0.223205763500991)], 1),
     (18.6491453242771, [(0.223205763500991, 0.974771351210088)], 1)]
  </output>
  </sage>
  <p>
    Since Sage does not sort the result by default we must use the <c>sort</c> 
    method to complete <em>step 6</em> and put our largest eigenvalue at the front.
  </p>
  <sage>
  <input>
    E.sort(reverse=True)
    E
  </input>
  <output>
    [(18.6491453242771, [(0.223205763500991, 0.974771351210088)], 1),
     (2.34904661787163, [(0.974771351210088, -0.223205763500991)], 1)]
  </output>
  </sage>
  <p>
    We will now access out our first principal component and reduce our data with respect to its eigenspace to plot it.
  </p>
  <sage>
  <input>
    v_1 = E[0][1][0]
    v_1
  </input>
  <output>
    (0.223205763500991, 0.974771351210088)
  </output>
  </sage>
  <p>
    We must now create our projection matrix:
  </p>
  <sage>
  <input>
    P_V1 = matrix(RR, [v_1, (0,0)]) # Projection mapping matrix
    P_V1
  </input>
  <output>
    [0.223205763500991 0.974771351210088]
    [0.000000000000000 0.000000000000000]
  </output>
  </sage>
  <p>
    We can then plot our transformed data on the <m>x</m>-axis.
  </p>
  <sage>
  <input>
  scatter_plot([P_V1 * x_i for x_i in D])
  </input>
  <output>
    Graphics object consisting of 1 graphics primitive
  </output>
  </sage>
  <p>
    We can now see that despite being lower dimensional, 
    the clustering of the data along the first principal component is preserved.
  </p>
</subsection>
</section>
